[Norovirus is a highly contagious virus. Anyone can experience norovirus infection. There are many genotypes of norovirus in circulation and reinfection can occur throughout life. Hence infected with one norovirus genotype does not provide life-long immunity. Thus, as in the current situation, the elderly are equally vulnerable to infection. Norovirus can be present in an infected person's faeces both before and after appearance of clinical disease.

Norovirus can spread quickly in closed places like daycare centers, nursing homes, schools, and cruise ships. Generally norovirus outbreaks happen from November to April in the northern hemisphere, hence the alternate designation of this infection as "Winter vomiting disease." Norovirus infection is also a leading cause of illness from contaminated food. Fatalities are rare, except among the elderly and infirm.

So far there has been no confirmation by laboratory analysis (a straight-forward procedure in the case of norovirus infection) that the illnesses and deaths that have occurred at the Shunko-kai Higashi Hospital in southern Miyazaki prefecture are a consequence of norovirus infection, but it is the likely diagnosis. In the absence of identification of the etiological agent it is illogical to attribute the deaths to a 'mutant' virus (or even a virus). Further information is waited.

Miyazaki prefecture can be located in the map at: http://www.ayaengei.com/e_contact.html. - Mod.CP

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1rMj.]
